column168: I WAS CALLED TO RESPOND TO A LEAKER IN UNLOAD Z. WEARING FULL P.P.E. I FOUND A 5 PART HAZMAT WITH A STAIN IN SIDE, CONSULTED DECISION TREE, AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS. WEARING PROPER PPE, I RESPONDED TO UNLOAD DOOR 8. I TOOK AFFECTED PACKAGE TO CAGE. UPON INSPECTION I LOCATED A LOOSE CAP. I TIGHTED CAP AND TESTED FOR LEAKAGE WHICH PROVED TO BE O.K. THESE JUGS WERE CLEANED OFF AND SENT BACK TO SHIPPER USING YELLOW HAZ-MAT RETURN TUBS. I THEN DMN'D THE CARDBOARD AND PAPER AFFECTED BY SPILL. I THEN DECONTAMINATED MY P.PE. SHIPPER IS TO BE NOTIFIED OF LOOSE CAPS.

INITIATING EVENT: EQUIPMENT FAILURE ROOT CAUSE: FROZEN VALVE SEAT INCIDENT DESCRIPTION: SOURCE VALVE SEAT THAWED AFTER FREEZING DURING PRIOR RAILCAR UNLOADING PROCEDURE.  ANOTHER RAILCAR UNLOADING PROCEDURE WAS PERFORMED UP STREAM FROM THE LEAK SOURCE.  LEAK OCCURRED WHEN LIQUID AMMONIA SEAPED PAST THE UNSEATED VALVE AND THROUGH THREADS OF LOOSE SECONDARY CLOSURE.  LEAK WAS OBSERVED BY OPERATOR AND TRANSFER WAS IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN.  OPERATOR THEN OPENED VALVES TO EVACUATE TRANSFER LINES INTO WATER ABSORBER SYSTEM.

column168: PASCHALL TRUCK LINES ARRIVED AT THE CONSIGNEE TO UNLOAD.  AFTER THE CONSIGNEE UNLOADED ABOUT HALF OF THE LOAD THEY DISCOVERED THAT THERE WAS PRODUCT SPILLED ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  PASCHALL CONTACTED EMI AND A CONTRACTOR WAS SENT FROM COLUMBUS OHIO TO TAKE CARE OF THE SPILL.  THE CLEAN-UP CREW ESTIMATED 5 TO 10 GALLONS OF PRODUCT HAD SPILLED ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER FROM A NAIL PUNCTURE TO THE BOTTOM OF ONE OF THE 55 GALLON DRUMS.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED IN AN OVERPACK AND PLACED BACK ON OUR DRIVER.  THE CLEAN-UP CREW WAS IN CHARGE OF THE DISPOSAL AND THE PASCHALL DRIVER TOOK THE OVERPACK BACK TO THE SHIPPER.

ON 09/05/00 AT APPROXIMATELY 1400 HOURS, A CN/IC SWITCH CREW NOTED LIQUID COMING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR UTLX 46753 (LOAD, METHANOL) DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS IN THE DESTRAHAN YARD, DESTRAHAN, LA. TANK CAR ISOLATED AND APPROPRIATE DEPARTMENTS NOTIFIED.  CN/IC HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED AND NOTED THAT FOUR OF EIGHT MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE LOOSE.  SHIPPER'S RESPONSE TEAM PROPERLY SECURED THE MANWAY COVER AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  TANK CAR RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER AT THEIR REQUEST.

DOCK WORKER STRUCK DRUM AND NOTIFIED ME THAT HE TURNED THE DRUM UPSIDE DOWN SO IT WOULD STOP LEAKING. I SAW THE SPILL AND HAD THE TRAILER PULLED OUT ONTO THE FAR LOT AND CALLED TERMINAL MGR.. AND THE RECOVERY COMPANY.

WHEN LOADING DRUM ON BACK OF TRAILER WITH A DRUM PICKER, FORKLIFT OPERATOR SET DRUMS DOWN AND THEN BEGAN TO BACK FORKLIFT UP. THE DRUM HAD NOT COMPLETELY RELEASED FROM THE DRUM PICKER WHEN HE DID THIS AND  WHEN HE BACKED UP IT CAUGHT THE DOCK PLATE WHICH SUBSEQUENTLY PUT A VERY SMALL HOLE IN IT. PUNCTURED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND SHIPPED TO ULTIMATE CONSIGNEE.

column168: DURING INSPECTION, PRIOR TO TENDERING TO CARIBBEAN TRANSPORTATION SERVICES. IT WAS NOTICED THAT THE STEEL DRUM WAS LEAKING FORM THE VALVE OR FITTING. IT WAS A VERY SLOW DRIP. THERE WAS NO PUDDLE. THE CARBOARD UNDER THE STEEL DRUM ABSORBED WHAT LITTLE LEAKED OUT. WE IMMEDIATELY STOWED THE STEEL DRUM IN A SALVAGE CONTAINER.

DRIVER BROUGHT TRAILER INTO YARD AND PROCEEDED TO CHECK TRAILER. HE OPENED THE DOORS AT THE BACK OF TRAILER AND NOTICED A VERY STRONG ODOR. HE NOTIFIED DART TRUCKING COMPANY, INC. SAFETY DEPARTMENT. DART PROCEEDED TO CONTACT POLLUTION CONTROL AND THEY GAVE DART THE APPROVAL TO CONTACT A RESPONSE CREW. DART SAFETY DEPARTMENT CONTACTED CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES. CLEAN HARBORS RESPONDED. UPON INSPECTION OF THE TRAILER CLEAN HARBORS LOCATED THE LEAKING DRUM. THEY THEN  PROCEEDED TO CLEAN UP TRAILER, TIGHTEN THE LID ON THE DRUM AND  OVERPACK THE DRUM.
THE DRUM WAS DAMAGED WHEN IT WAS UNLOADED AT ELEMENTIS PERFORMANCE IN CLIFTON, NJ. A SMALL AMOUNT OF THE CONTENTS LEAKED OUT.

column62: Abrasion; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails); Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: DRIVER BROUGHT LOAD INTO SAN MARTIN YARD TO TRANSFER OTHER ITEMS ONTO THE TRAILER. WHILE ADJUSTING THE LOAD HE OBSERVED A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE LEFT FRONT OF THE TRAILER ONTO THE ASPHALT DRUM PAD. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION HE DISCOVERED THAT TRANSFORMER # 2183, LOADED NEXT TO # 2184, ON A WOODEN PALETT HAD SHIFTED AND MOVED AGAINST 2184. A LARGE PROTRUDING BOLT ON THE TRANSFORMER WAS LOOSENED AND THE PCB INSIDE BEGAN SLOWLY SEEPING OUT. APPARENTLY THE SEEPAGE BEGAN WHEN THE VEHICLE WAS BROUGHT INTO THE SAN MARTIN YARD AS NO EVIDENCE OF IT LEAKING PRIOR TO THAT WAS FOUND. ALL OF THE TRANSFORMERS WERE RELOADED INTO PLASTIC HALF BOXES, THE LEAKING TRANSFORMER WAS STOPPED, ABSORPTION SWEEP WAS USED TO PICK UP WHAT HAD LEAKED. PLACED IN A 5 GAL PAN AND DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: DURING STRIPPING OF PICKUP UNIT, A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL WAS FOUND TO HAVE LEAKED OUT OF A BAG OF MATERIAL. IT APPEARED THAT DURING LOADING A SHIPPER LOCATION, THE SKID LOADED NEXT TO IT GOT RUBBED DOWN THE SIDE RESULTING IN A SMALL HOLE. CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED WHO IN TURN CONTACTED BAYER CORP. MATERIAL CLEANED UP AND SECURED AS PER INSTRUCTED. DAMAGED BAG RETURNED TO SHIP LOCATION. CORRECTIVE ACTION IS PLACING OF DUNNAGE IN BETWEEN BAGGED MATERIAL DURING LOADING AT SHIP LOCATION.

A TRUCK WAS BEING UNLOADED AND THE WASTE TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TRUCK BY A FORKLIFT. A 5 GALLON POLY DRUM WAS ON A PALLET TO BE TRANSFERRED WHEN IT WAS PUNCTURED BY THE FORKLIFT. APPROXIMATELY 1.5 GALLONS OF AN AQUEOUS BRAKE SOLUTION SPILLED FROM THE DRUM INTO THE BACK OF THE TRUCK. THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT AND CONTAINERIZED INTO  AND OVERPACK ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL MATERIAL. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 20 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 633 E 138TH STREET IN DOLTON , IL FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE FORKLIFT DIRVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER FORKLIFT TECHNIQUES AND WASTE HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

A 55 GALLON STEEL DRUM OF FLAMMABLE LIQUID WAS IN TEMPORARY STORAGE IN A SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AT A TEN DAY STORAGE FACILITY WHEN THE MATERIAL INSIDE BEGAN TO POLYMERIZE. THE DRUM BURST FROM THE BOTTOM AND FLEW UP HITTING THE ROOF. THE MAJORITY OF THE MATERIAL HAD POLYMERIZED INTO A SOLID MATERIAL RESEMBLING STYROFOAM. THE LIQUID MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT AND CONTAINERIZED ALONG WITH THE SOLID MATERIAL. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 450 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 6125 N. PECATONICA ROAD, IN PECATONICA, IL FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER WASTE INSPECTION PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: RAIL SWITCHING YARD CROSSING CITY STREET. TRUCK & TRAIN COLLIDED. MANY RAIL CARS ON OTHER TRACKS, BLOCKING VISION. NO LIGHTS, ARMS OR FLAG MAN.

TOP AND BOTTOM OF DRUM HAD PIN HOLES RESULTING IN LOSS OF MATERIAL. DRIVER PICKED UP TRAILER LOAD IN CINNAMINSON, NJ ON 9/20/00. AFTER PICKING UP THE LOAD THE DRIVERS INSPECTED THE DRUMS AND SECURED THE LOAD, HE THEN STARTED TO DRIVE HEADED TO HIS DESIGNATED FACILITY IN CHARLOTTE, NC. HE PULLED OFF INTO A TRUCK STOP ON ROUTE 301 IN MIDDLETOWN, DE TO TAKE A FEW MINUTE BREAKS, PRIOR TO GOING INTO THE TRUCK STOP FACILITY, HE CHECKED THE LOAD HE HAD ON AND DISCOVERED THAT THERE WAS A DRUM LEAKING. IN AN EFFORT TO STOP THE DRUM FROM LEAKING HE TRIED TO OVER PACK THE DRUM, HOWEVER THE DRUM HAD A HOLE ON THE TOP AND ALSO ON THE BOTTOM. AT THIS POINT IT BECAME DIFFICULT FOR THE DRIVER TO OVERPAK THE DRUM. HE CALLED OUR DISPATCH AND HELP WAS GOTTEN TO FOR  HIM TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL WHICH ABOUT 12 GALLONS OR 100 LBS.  AFTER THE RESPONSE TEAM COMPLETED THE CLEAN UP, THE DRIVER WAS RELEASED AND WAS ABLE TO RETURN TO HIS HOME TERMINAL.

column168: CCX EMPLOYEE WAS LOADING TRAILER WITH LONG STEEL PUSHING STEEL IN TO BOTTOM OF PLASTIC DRUM THIS PUNCTURED SMALL HOLE IN BOTTOM OF 1 DRUM. DRUM WAS QUICKLY LAID OVER TO PREVENT ANYMORE LEAKAGE THEN WAS PUT IN LARGE METAL SALVAGE DRUM. EMPLOYEE WAS GIVEN A LETTER ON POOR LOADING AND HAS BEEN RETRAINED.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Corrosion - Exterior
column168: MATERIAL LEAKED OUT OF TOP OF ONE BOTTLE. IT WAS DISCOVERED ACCIDENTALLY, THEREFORE WHERE/WHEN LEAK OCCURRED IS UNKNOWN. LIQUID HAD CORRODED THROUGH BOTTOM OF BOX, AND SOILED CORRODED TOP OF ANOTHER AND SIDE OF 2 MORE. NO EVIDENCE OF ROUGH HANDLING EXISTS. NO EVIDENCE BOXES HAD BEEN OPENED. LEAKING JUG WAS IN MIDDLE OF CASE. SUSPECT FAULTY CAP. COPY OF CHEM. INCIDENT REPORT SENT TO ORIGIN TERMINAL MANAGER FOR ANY FOLLOW-UP ACTION(S) HE MAY DEEM APPROPRIATE/ NECESSARY

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: ON 9-13 AT APPROX 0230 STAN NEVIN CAME TO ME AND SAID HE HAD A HAZ-MAT SPILL. HE INFORMED ME THAT HE HAD PUT HIS FORKS THROUGH A SMALL SKID AND THAT HE PUT HIS FOOT ON THE MOTOR  BRAKE BUT IT STILL WENT FORWARD ENOUGH TO PUNCTURE THE DRUM IN FRONT OF THE SKID. WE THEN PUT THE DRUM IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND PUT FLOOR DRY AROUND THE LIQUID TO CONTAIN THE SPILL. AFTER THE SPILL WAS ABSORBED WE PUT THE USED FLOOR DRY IN 2 RECOVERY DRUMS IN THE HAZ-MAT AREA WITH THE OTHER DRUMS WITH COPIES OF THE BILLS ON EACH OF THEM.

DSR LOADED THIS FREIGHT ON A HOLDING TRAP TRAILER, DID NOT BLOCK THIS FREIGHT IN, ALSO DID NOT PUSH FREIGHT UP FAR ENOUGH AGAINST OTHER FREIGHT. WHEN TRAILER WAS MOVED. FREIGHT SHIFTED CAUSING ALL OF THE BAGS TO FALL OVER, CAUSING DAMAGE TO THE FREIGHT.
WHILE BACKING OUT OF THE TRAILER THE DRIVER TURNED TO SHARPLY, TO FAST OR BOTH, CAUSING THE TOTE TO TIP OVER. UPON IMPACT WITH THE DOCK, THE LID POPPED OFF CAUSING THE SPILL.

column42: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE AND PEROXYACETIC ACID MIXTURES, STABILIZED WITH ACIDS, WATER, AND NOT MORE THAN 5 PERCENT PEROXYACETIC ACID
column168: BOX WAS NOT DAMAGED UPON ARRIVAL, BUT WAS NOTED AS "WET" WHILE STAGED ON DOCK.  BOX MAY HAVE BEEN KNOCKED OVER OR BUMPED.  NO ONE CLAIMS TO HAVE DONE IT, OR SEEN WHAT HAPPENED.  ONLY ONE BOTTLE WAS DAMAGED, BUT IT SOILED ALL INSIDE BOX.  DAMAGED BOTTLE SHOWED EVIDENCE OF HAVING BEEN STRUCK/DROPPED, BUT IT WAS ON SIDE/MIDDLE.

FORKLIFT OPERATOR PUNCTURED DRUM WITH FORK WHILE MANEUVERING ADJACENT FREIGHT.  DRUM WAS ONTO SIDE TO MINIMIZE AMOUNT SPILLING OUT.  FORKLIFT DRIVER WILL RECEIVE INCIDENT REPORT, AND RETRAINING/RECERTIFICATION ON ATTENTIVE FORKLIFT OPERATION.

FREIGHT WAS STACKED ON TOP OF TOTE AND CAME INTO CONTACT WITH SPRING HELD CAP ON TOP OF TOTE.  FREIGHT SHIFTED AND SPRING RELEASED CAP CAME OFF.  WHILE IN TRANSIT MOVEMENT OF TRAILER CAUSED LIQUID INSIDE TOTE TO SPILL OUT OF TOP OF TOTE ALL OVER TRAILER FLOOR AND CHEMICAL INCIDENT REPORT.  CAP WAS NOT DAMAGED AND WAS RE-SECURED TO TOTE TO PREVENT FURTHER SPILLAGE.  WILL ADVISE ALL PERSONAL THAT LOAD TRAILERS TO NOT TOP LOAD CHEMICAL TOTES TO PREVENT FURTHER INCIDENTS OF THIS TYPE.
WHILE UNLOADING, DOCKMAN WENT TO GET THIS SKID AND FORKLIFT PUNCTURED DRUM ON OTHER SIDE OF THIS PALLET.  APPROXIMATELY 1/2 PINT LEAKED OUT.
COPIES OF THIS DOCUMENTS WILL BE GIVEN TO THE SUPERVISOR FOR TRAINING WITH THEIR PEOPLE.

column14: HWY I-65 NORTH OF MOBILE 500 Y
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 8:30 A.M. ON 9-14-2000, A DELTA/BRENNTAG TRACTOR PULLING A 28' PUP TRAILER WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON I-65.  WE WERE HAULING AMMONIUM CHLORIDE, 330-GALLON TOTE TANKS OF HcL, AND DRUMS OF CAUSTIC SODA.  WE EXPERIENCED TOTE TANK FAILURE(A 2' VERTICAL SPLIT IN THE HcL TANK) BETWEEN THE 4 AND 5 MILE MARKER, WHICH IS 500-600 YARDS NORTH OF THE AIRPORT BLVD. EXIT ON I-65.  AT THAT TIME OUR DRIVER (RALEIGH CLARKE) NOTICED LARGE AMOUNTS OF HcL FUMES COMING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER AND HE PULLED THE TRUCK TO THE LEFT SIDE OF THE INTERSTATE TO INVESTIGATE THE PROBLEM.  HE NOTICED HcL LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER AND IMMEDIATELY VACATED THE AREA.  AN EMT UNIT OF THE MOBILE FIRE DEPT. ALSO SAW THE PROBLEM AND RESPONDED.  THE EMT UNIT NOTIFIED THE MOBILE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE MOBILE HAZMAT AND POLICE DEPARTMENTS. SAFEGUARDS WERE QUICKLY PUT INTO PLACE AND NEUTRALIZATION OF THE HcL WAS STARTED IMMEDIATELY WITH SODA ASH. AT THAT TIME I CONTACTED UNITED STATES. ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES L.L.C., COMPANY LICENSED BY THE STATE OF ALABAMA FOR HAZARDOUS WASTE REMOVAL.  USES RESPONDED WITHIN 15 MINUTES AND WAS ON THE SCENE WITHIN 30 MINUTES.  THE ENTIRE SPILL WAS COMPLETELY CLEANED AND  ALL EQUIPMENT WAS REMOVED AND TRAFFIC WAS AGAIN USING ALL LANES OF I-65 BY 12:30 P.M.  I AM ALSO PLEASED TO REPORT THAT THERE WERE NO INJURIES TO ANY DELTA/BRENNTAG, CITY OF MOBILE OR CONTRACTOR PERSONNEL INVOLVED WITH THE CLEAN-UP.

column168: OUR EMPTY TRAILER WAS IN THE SHIPPERS PLANT TO LOAD TWO DIFFERENT PRODUCTS.  AFTER THE PLANT COMPLETED LOADING THE TRAILER WITH THE TWO PRODUCTS THE OPERATOR DISCOVERED PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE BELLY OF OUR TRAILER AT THE INTERNAL VALVE FLANGE.  THE PLANT THEN UNLOADED THE PRODUCT FROM OUR TRAILER BACK INTO THERE STORAGE TANK.

DRIVER ARRIVED AT LOCATION.  HE TOOK SAMPLE INTO CONSIGNER AND LOOKED AT OUTAGE ON TANK.  HE THEN WENT OUT AND STARTED TO UNLOAD. THE CONSIGNEE DID NOT TELL HIM IT WAS OK TO START UNLOADING.  DRIVER FINISHED UNLOADING PUP TRAILER AND WAS STARTING TO UNLOAD THE MAIN TRAILER, WHEN TANK OVERFLOWED.  HE IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN PUMP.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN CONCRETE PIT.  THE DRIVER THEN STARTED TO UNHOOK HOSE AND SPILLED AN ADDITIONAL 15-20 GALLONS ON THE GROUND. THE SPILL IN THE PIT WAS PUMPED OUT AND DISPOSED OF.  THE SPILL FROM THE HOSES WAS EXCAVATED AND SOIL WAS PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.  DRIVER WAS DISCHARGED FOR FAILURE TO FOLLOW COMPANY PROCEDURES WHEN UNLOADING.

column168: (A & B) ON SEPTEMBER 3, 2000, CSX TRAIN Q61831 DERAILED NEAR LAWRENCEVILLE, GA.  ETCX 657 AND UTLX 46900 WERE TWO OF 14 CARS DERAILED. ETCX 657 RECIEVED A HOLD IN THE LEFT SIDE, APPROXIMATELY 12 FEET LONG AND 3 FEET WIDE IN THE MIDDLE OF THE CAR.  ALSO, A HOLE WAS FOUND BELOW THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING FOR THE LIQUID AND VAPOR VALVES ON THE LEFT SIDE.  THIS HOLE WAS 6 INCHES LONG AND 3 INCHES WIDE.  THIS CAR LOST ITS CONTENTS ON IMPACT.  UTLX 46900 SUFFERED A RIP IN THE SHELL 1 FOOT TOWARD THE A END FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  THIS RIP WAS 2 FEET LONG AND 6 INCHES WIDE. THE RELIEF VALVE ON THIS CAR WAS SHEARED COMPLETELY AWAY.  THE CONTENTS OF THIS CAR WERE TRANSLOADED INTO ANOTHER TANK CAR AND THE CAR WAS CLEANED ON SITE. (C - E) GATX 51722 LOST PRODUCT FROM THE MANWAY AND THE LEAK STOPPED WHEN PRODUCT LEVEL DROPPED BELOW THE MANWAY LEVEL.  THE MANWAY BOLTS WRE FOUND TIGHT AND THE GASKET WAS IN GOOD CONDITION.  THE CONTENTS OF THE CAR WERE TRANSFERRED INTO ANOTHER TANK CAR AND THE CAR WAS CLEANED ON SITE. UTLX 46543 A HOLE IN THE B-END HEAD IN THE 8:00 O'CLOCK POSITION.  THE HOLE WAS APPRODIMATELY 18 INCHES LON AND 2.5 INCHES WIDE.  THE HOLE WAS PLUGGED WHEN ACCESS COULD BE OBTAINED AFTER MOVING OTHER INVOLVED RAILCARS.  THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS PUMPED OUT AND THE CAR WAS CLEANED ON SITE.  UTLX 46592 SUFFERED A COMPLETED SHEARING AWAY OF THE BOTTOM OUTLET ASSEMBLY, INCLUDING THE VALVE.  THE HOLE WAS PLUGGED WHEN ACCESS COULD BE OBTAINED AFTER MOVING OTHER INVOLVED CARS.  THE REMAINING PRODUCT IN THE CAR WAS PUMPED OUT AND THE CAR WAS CLEANED ON SITE. (F) THIS CAR AN IMPACT IN TH DERAILMENT RESULTING IN A HOLE IN THE A-END LEFT BOTTOM CORNER OF THE HEAD.  THIS HOLE WAS APPROXIMATELY 5 INCHES LONG AND 3 INCHES WIDE. PRODUCT LEAKAGE FROM THE HOLE COULT NOT BE STOPPED UNTIL OTHER CARS WERE REMOVED FROM THE AREA.  WHEN THE CAR WAS REACHED, THE HOLE WAS PLUGGED BY CSXT RESPONSE CONTRACTOR PERSONNEL.  THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS REMOVED AND THE CAR WAS CLEANED ON SITE.

APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE PAIL WAS DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING. H.M.H.T.T.C. PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL D PROTECTION, OIL DRY, AND ABSORBENT PADS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO TWO, 30 GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUMS.  BOTH RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE DISPOSED OF BY H.M.H.T.T.C.   THE DAMAGED PAIL WAS PLACED INTO THE TERMINAL'S WASTE RECEPTACLE.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. WHILE EN ROUTE ON INTERSTATE 80, THE DRIVER NOTICED FREE PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER.  HE PULLED OVER AT STEVEN'S CITY SCALES IN STEVENS CITY, VA TO INVESTIGATE THE LEAK.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE DAMAGED 55-GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED INSIDE THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY 30 GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE WAS DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING IN TRANSIT.  H.M.H.T.T.C., OF PARISIPPANY, NJ, WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  H.M.H.T.T.C. PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING SPEEDY-DRY.  THERE WAS NO SOIL OR WATER AFFECTED AS A RESULT OF THE RELEASE.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A 55 GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUM.  THE STEEL RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE DISPOSED OF BY H.M.H.T.T.C..  THE  DAMAGED 55 GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS PLACED INTO AN 85 GALLON STEEL OVERPACK DRUM.  THE OVERPACK DRUM WILL BE SENT BACK TO THE ROADWAY EXPRESS, INCORPORATED, IN CARLISLE, PA AND HELD FOR DISPOSAL.  THERE WAS NO REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO BE FORWARDED.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE ON THE DOCK, AT THE TERMINAL A DOCK WORKER DISCOVERED A LEAKING, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC DRUM.  APPROXIMATELY FOUR OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE LEAKAGE FROM THE DRUM WAS DUE TO A LOOSE VALVE.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL D PROTECTION.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE VALVE ON THE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUM WAS TIGHTENED AND WILL BE  RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: WHILE AT THE TERMINAL, THE DRIVER DISCOVERED A LEAK AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT THREE OF THE JARS WERE DAMAGED, AND ONE OF THE JARS WAS UNAFFECTED.  APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE JARS WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY ADJACENT FREIGHT.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL B PROTECTION.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, FREE PRODUCT, WET CARTON, DAMAGED JARS, UNAFFECTED JAR, AND REMAINING PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO ONE, TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, ONE, 55 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, ONE, 15 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, AND ONE, 15 GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUM. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE WET CARTON CONTAINING THREE, 0.5-GALLON CONTAINERS WAS DISCOVERED IN THE THIRD QUARTER OF THE TRAILER.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ALL THREE CONTAINERS WERE DAMAGED.  APPROXIMATELY ONE TEASPOON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND ABSORBED INTO THE CARTON.  APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO HEAVY TOPFREIGHT.  TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEAN-UP USING LEVEL D PROTECTION.  THE DAMAGED CONTAINERS, AFFECTED CARTON, AND THE CLEAN-UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 5-GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THERE WAS NO REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE ON THE DOCK, ONE CARTON CONTAINING FOUR, 1-GALLON CONTAINERS WAS DAMAGED.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE CONTAINER WAS DAMAGED AND THREE WERE UNAFFECTED.  APPROXIMATELY ONE PINT OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A FORKLIFT PUNCTURE.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN-UP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE DAMAGED CONTAINER AND THE AFFECTED CARDBOARD WERE PLACED INTO A 5-GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUM.  THE CLEAN-UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A SECOND 5-GALLON POLY RECOVERY DRUM.  BOTH RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE THREE UNAFFECTED CONTAINERS WERE RECOUPED INTO A CARDBOARD BOX AND WILL BE FORWARDED ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: WHILE IN THE TERMINAL YARD, FREE PRODUCT WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER. APPARENTLY THE TOTE BIN WAS LEAKING FROM A CRACKED VALVE THAT WAS PUNCTURED BY ADJACENT FREIGHT.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED CLEANUP USING LEVEL C.  ABSORBENT MATERIALS WERE USED TO CONTAIN THE FREE PRODUCT. HAZMAT ONE WAS CONTACTED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP OF THE REMAINING PRODUCT.  THE LEAKING TOTE WAS PLACED INTO A CONTAINMENT POOL AT THE TERMINAL.  THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED INTO FOUR, 55-GALLON PLASTIC DRUMS.  THE FOUR PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER ALONG WITH THE EMPTY TOTE PER SHIPPER'S INSTRUCTIONS.  THE ABSORBENT MATERIALS AND CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO TWO, 114-LITER PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUMS.  THE CONTAINMENT POOL WAS PLACED INTO A 55-GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM.  THE PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column42: ORGANIC PEROXIDE TYPE D, LIQUID, TEMPERATURE CONTROLLED
column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS ORIGINALLY PICKED UP IN A ROCOR REFRIGERATED TRAILER AT PENGUAL PETRO QUIMICA, VERA CRUZ, MEXICO, BY TRANSPORTES LAR-MEX FOR TRANSPORTATION TO THE BORDER (NUEVO LAREDO, MEXICO). UPON ARRIVAL AT THE BORDER, THE SHIPMENT WAS DELAYED 12 DAYS WHILE WAITING TO BE CLEARED BY CUSTOMS.  WE UNDERSTAND THE DELAY WAS DUE TO "INVALID TARIFF NUMBERS", WHICH WERE FINALLY RESOLVED AND THE TRAILER PICKED UP BY AUTO TRANSPORTES CHARLIE ON 9/1/00 TO BRING ACROSS THE BORDER TO J. O. ALVAREZ, LAREDO, TX.  UPON ARRIVAL AT J. O. ALVAREZ, THE REEFER UNIT WAS FOUND TO BE EMPTY AND NOT RUNNING. IT WAS RE-FUELED AND STARTED.  ON 9/4/00, FUMES WERE OBSERVED COMING FROM THE TRAILER AND THE LAREDO FIRE DEPT WAS CALLED.  ADDITIONALLY, AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM (ERT) RESPONDED TO THIS INCIDENT. APPARENTLY, THE ORGANIC PEROXIDE WAS DECOMPOSING GIVING OFF SMOKE AND FUMES, WHICH ALERTED PERSONNEL OF THE PROBLEM.  SEVERAL PEOPLE IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA (2BLOCKS) COMPLAINED ABOUT THE FOUL SMELL AND WENT TO THE HOSPITAL WHERE THEY WERE CHECKED AND RELEASED.  NO ONE WAS HOSPITALIZED.  THE ERT AND THE FIRE DEPT DID THEIR JOBS AND THE INCIDENT WAS RESOLVED.  THE ACTUAL CAUSES OF THE INCIDENT ARE STILL BEING INVESTIGATED WITH THE CARRIER(S) WHO BROUGHT IF FROM ACTUAL ORIGIN TO THE BORDER AND SUBSEQUENTLY TO THE U. S.  IT IS SUSPECTED THAT THE LACK OF REFRIGERATION OR INCORRECT TEMPERATURES FOR A PERIOD OF TIME, MAY HAVE CAUSED OR CONTRIBUTED TO THE INCIDENT.

THREE DRUMS WITH ONE LAYER OF SHRINKWRAP CAME LOOSE AND SHIFTED ON PALLET.  WHEN SHIFTING, TIPPED OVER AND BROKE THROUGH PALLET CAUSING DRUM TO BE PUNCTURED.  NOTICED SMOKE FROM CHEMICAL REACTION COMING OUT BACK OF TRAILER.

THEREFORE, PRODUCT LEAKED ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR AND OUT ONTO THE GROUND.  EMI WAS CONTACTED AND THEY SENT A CLEAN-UP CREW OUT OF DALLAS TO TAKE CARE OF THE SPILL.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND DISPOSAL SOLUTIONS WAS IN CHARGE OF THE DISPOSAL.  OUR DRIVER CONTINUED ON TO HIS NEXT APPOINTMENT.

ON SEPTEMBER 8, 2000 A 5200-GALLON VAC TRAILER, WHICH WAS PARKED AT CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC'S.  (CHESI) 10 DAY TRUCK-TO-TRUCK TRANSFER FACILITY, LOCATED AT 2930 INDEPENDENCE ROAD, CLEVELAND,  OHIO 44115 HAD AN EXTERNAL VALVE FAIL, CAUSING APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF HAZARDOUS WASTE TO SPILL ONTO THE GROUND.  THE MATERIAL INSIDE WAS HAZARDOUS WASTE LIQUID N.O.S. (CHROMIUM) 9, NA 3082 PG III.  THE MATERIAL WAS IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP BY CHESI PERSONNEL. THE CAUSE OF THE EXTERNAL VALVE FAILURE WAS MECHANICAL.  THE VALVE WAS REPLACED.

THIS IS A REPLACEMENT SHIPMENT FOR ONE OF THE 8 PIECES FROM 09/20/00 WHERE ONE OF THE PIECES WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN POSSIBLE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS. THERE ARE NO MARKINGS OR LABELINGS ON THE PACKAGE AND NO DANGEROUS GOODS PAPERWORK WAS OFFERED TO FEDEX. THE MSDS STATES THAT THIS CONTAINES 19 % ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL AND A FLASHPOINT GREATER THAN 60 DEGREES FARENHEIT. SINCE THERE IS NO SPECIFIC FLASHPOINT FOR THIS PRODUCT AND A SOLUTION WITH 19% ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL COULD BE FLAMMABLE, THIS PACKAGE IS BEING HELD AT OUR FOPRT FEDEX LOCATION FOR FAA INVESTIGATION AS A POSSIBLE HIDDEN DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY THE STATION'S SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST PER FEDEX POLICY.

THIS PACKAGE SPILL WAS FOUND TO BE POSSIBLE HIDDEN DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT WHEN THE MSDS WAS SENT TO THE FEDEX STATION BY THE COMPANY THAT MANUFACTURES THIS MATERIAL. THE FLASHPOINT IS LISTED AS GREATER THAN 60 DEGREES FARENHEIT. THIS MATERIAL HAS 19% ISOPROPOL ALCOHOL IN IT, SO THE FLASHPOINT MAY FALL BELOW THE 141 DEGREE UPPER LIMIT FOR A FLAMMABLE LIQUID. NO EXACT FLASHPOINT IS AVAILABLE FOR THIS LIQUID. THE MANUFACTURER AND THE SHIPPER CLAIM THAT THIS LIQUID IS NON HAZARDOUS. NO TRANSPORTATION INFORMATION IS AVAILABLE ON THE MSDS. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP PER FEDEX POLICY AND PROCEDURES AND 7 OF THE 8 PIECES ARE BEING HELD FOR AN FAA INVESTIGATION BECAUSE OF THE 19% ALCOHOL CONTENT. ONE OF THE PACKAGES IN THIS SHIPMENT WAS DELIVERED BEFORE THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD FOR THE FAA INVESTIGATION. NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKINGS OR LABELINGS WERE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE AND NO DANGEROUS GOODS PAPERWORK WAS GIVEN TO FEDEX FOR THIS SHIPMENT.

column168: DERAILMENT, NO RELEASE, EVACUATION ONLY, CITX 32146, SEPTEMBER 29, 2000, NORTH JERSEY DIVISION AT APPROXIMATELY 0415 HOURS, FRIDAY, SEPTEMBER 29, 2000, WHILE SHOVING BACK ON BARBER SIDING TO SHELL LEAD,  WOODBRIDGE, NEW JERSEY, CONRAIL TRAIN YPPR61 RAN OVER DERAIL, DERAILING TANK CAR CITX 32146 CONTAINING LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS (BUTANE). HULCHER ARRIVED AT THE SITE AND RERAILED THE CARS.  EVACUATION LASTED APPROXIMATELY 90 MINUTES.  AT  APPROXIMATELY, 0850 HOURS, THE TANK CAR WAS RERAILED AND TRAIN SWITCHED INTO PLANT.

column168: CONTRACTOR WAS HIRED TO CLEAN TANKER. CONTRACTOR COULD NOT REMOVE THE RESIDUE MATERIAL. THE RESIDUE WAS ENROUTE BACK TO THE SHIPPER. DURING THE DRIVER'S REST PERIOD HE DISCOVERED A SMALL PUNCTURE IN THE INNER LINER OF THE INSULATED TANKER. HE CONTAINED THE DRIP AND ABSORBED THE REMAINING RESIDUE WITH OIL DRY. THE MATERIAL HAS BEEN REMOVED FROM THE TANKER AND REPAIR AND RE-TESTING WILL BE DONE PRIOR TO PUTTING BACK IN SERVICE.

column14: SWITCH TRACK ADJACENT TO C ST
column168: A STRING OF RAIL CARS WERE SCHEDULED TO BE MOVED TO WEIGH SCALE TRACK. SWITCHING CREW DISCUSSED THEIR PLANNED TASK PRIOR TO MOVEMENT OF RAIL CARS FROM ONE TRACK TO A DIFFERENT TRACK. SUBSEQUENTLY, FOUR RAIL CARS DERAILED DURING SWITCHING OPERATION. CAUSE OF DERAILMENT WAS MISALIGNED TRACK SWITCH DUE TO MISCOMMUNICATION AMONG PERSONNEL OF THE SWITCH CREWS. APPROXIMATELY 8 GALLONS OF REGISTERED PESTICIDE DMA 806BR CONTACTED THE GROUND NEXT TO TRACK FROM DOME OF DOWX 70319.

WEARING PROPER PPE I WENT TO TRAILER #9. I DISCOVERED 2 PACKAGES THAT HAD SPILLS IN OR ON THEM. I RETURNED TO THE REWRAP AREA. AFTER NOTICING IT WAS A CORROSIVE ( POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE). I PUT THE WASTE AND 2 GALLONS OF POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE THROUGH THE DMN. BECAUSE CAPS ON THE CHEMICAL WOULD NOT TIGHTEN DOWN. I CONCLUDED THERE WAS A DEFECT IN THE CAP. I PREPARED AND RETURNED THE REMAINING 2 GALLONS VIA THE YELLOW RETURN TUBS. I THEN DECONTAMINATED MY PPE.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: A PASSENGER PRESENTED A CHAINSAW (MOTORIZED) IN A HARD CASE TO A MIDWEST EXPRESS AGENT AT THE MIDWEST EXPRESS TICKET COUNTER IN NEWARK, NJ, TO BE CHECKED AS BAGGAGE ON FLIGHT 279 ON 9-14-00.  THE AGENT DID NOT QUESTION IF THE MOTORIZED EQUIPMENT CONTAINED FUEL. DURING THE OFFLOADING PROCESS AT THE DESTINATION AIRPORT (MILWAUKEE, WI), A RAMP AGENT NOTICED A SMELL OF FUEL AND TRACED THE SMELL TO THE CHAINSAW, FINDING GASOLINE RESIDUE ON THE EXTERIOR OF THE CASE. THE ARTICLE WAS TAKEN TO THE BAGGAGE SERVICE OFFICE, WHERE IT WAS CLAIMED AND REMOVED BY THE PASSENGER WITHOUT FURTHER DISCUSSION WITH A MIDWEST EXPRESS AGENT.  THE QUANTITY OF FUEL CONTAINED IN THE UNIT, AND THE AMOUNT THAT MAY HAVE BEEN RELEASED IS UNKNOWN, BUT APPEARED TO HAVE ONLY BEEN ENOUGH TO LEAVE A RESIDUE ON THE EXTERIOR OF THE CASE.  ALL DANGEROUS GOODS PASSENGER NOTIFICATION SIGNAGE, AGENT TRAINING REQUIREMENTS AND RESOURCES ARE CURRENT AND FAA-APPROVED.  ADDITIONAL COACHING AND TRAINING WAS PROVIDED TO THE AGENT WHO ACCEPTED THE PIECE AS CHECKED BAGGAGE.

ENVIRONMENTAL PRODUCTS & SERVICES OF HARRISBURG, PA WERE DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. UPON INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE, DAMAGED FIFTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS LEAKING AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY FIVE GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE DRUM WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY TRAILER DEFECT. ENVIRONMENTAL  PRODUCT & SERVICES PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, A NEUTRALIZER AND FLOOR DRY. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND FREE PRODUCT WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A NINETY-FIVE GALLON OVERPACK DRUM. BOTH DRUMS WERE PLACED BACK ON THE TRAILER AND TRANSPORTED TO THE CONSOLIDATED FREIGHTWAYS, INC. CARLISLE, PA TERMINAL WHERE THEY WILL BE HELD FOR SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ON 09/18/00 AT APPROXIMATELY 1440 HOURS, A CN/IC EMPLOYEE NOTED LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE NOSE OF TRAILER BMDZ 630061 ( CORROSIVE LIQUID, ACIDIC,ORGANIC, NOS) WHILE PARKED IN THE CN/IC STYDOCK INTERMODAL TERMINAL, NEW ORLEANS,LA. TRAILER ISOLATED AND APPROPRIATE DEPARTMENTS NOTIFIED. CN/IC HAZMAT TEAM AND SHIPPER'S RESONSE CONTRACTOR RESPONDED. SHIPPER'S RESPONSE TEAM NOTED THAT A WELD ON THE FORK GUIDE BRACKET HAD A SMALL CRACK, ALLOWING LIQUID TO LEAK FROM THE PORTA-FEED. LADING TRANSLOADED INTO DRUMS. TRAILER DECONED AND RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

ON 09/19/00 AT APPROXIMATELY 1445 HOURS, A CN/IC SWITCH CREW NOTED VAPOR COMING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR RCRX 1347 (RESIDUE, LAST CONTAINED HYDROCHLORIC ACID) DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS IN THE DESTRAHAN YARD, DESTRAHAN,LA. TANK CAR ISOLATED AND APPROPRIATE DEPARTMENTS NOTIFIED. CN/IC HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED AND NOTED THAT THE SAFETY RELIEF DEVICE WAS STUCK IN THE OPEN POSITION, SPRING APPEARED TO BE LOOSE. WOODEN WEDGE USED TO TEMPORARY SECURE THE RELIEF VALVE. SHIPPER'S RESPONSE TEAM REPLACED THE RELIEF VALVE WITH A NEW ONE. TANK CAR RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.

CUSTOMER HAD CHECK VALVE IN INLET LINE WHICH FAILED TO OPEN. WHEN THE VALVE DID NOT OPEN IT CREATED EXCESSIVE PRESSURE IN THE LINE AND THE EXCESS PRESSURE CAUSED THE UNLOADING HOSE TO SPLIT. WHEN THE HOSE SPLIT IT RELEASED APPROXIMATLY 2-2&1/2 GALLONS OF MATERIAL TO SPILL. PRODUCT WAS CAUGHT IN CUSTOMERS CONTAINMENT AREA AND CUSTOMER CLEANED UP SPILLED PRODUCT. HOSES WERE REPLACED AND REST OF LOAD WAS UNLOADED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

CUSTOMER ORDERED & SIGNED FOR .3950 GALLON OF DIESEL FUEL- WE UNLOADED INTO THEIR STORAGE TANK THAT THEY SAID WOULD HOLD IT. THEIR GAUGE WAS BAD- PRODUCT OVERFILLED TANK & APX 75 GALLONS WENT INTO CONTAINMENT AREA.

DRIVER ARRIVED AT CONSIGNEE, AND IT WAS NOTED THAT A DRIP LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTER JACKET.  TRAILER CARGO TANK WAS PUT INTO THE CONSIGNEE'S CONTAINMENT AREA WITH DRIP PAN UNDER IT.  IT WAS WATCHED BY CONSIGNEE PERSONNEL UNTIL A DIFFERENT TRAILER CARGO TANK ARRIVED FOR THE TRANSFER OF PRODUCT FROM THE AFFECTED TRAILER. THERE WERE NO INJURIES, AND NO PRODUCT REACHED ANY WATERWAYS. SUBSEQUENT TESTING & EVALUATION SHOWED A WELD SEAM CRACK ABOUT 6 INCHES IN LENGTH ON ONE OF THE MANUFACTURING SECTION WELDS IN THE INNER VESSEL.

PRODUCT SAMPLES WERE TAKEN FROM THE VALVE BY THE CONSIGNEE REPRESENTATIVE.  WHEN RETURNED TO TAKE SECOND SAMPLE, PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM THE FLANGE FITTING THAT IS NEXT TO THE INTERNAL VALVE. THE BOLTS ON THE FLANGE FITTING WERE TIGHTENED AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED.  THE RELEASED PRODUCT (APPROXIMATELY 3 GALLONS) WAS CONTAINED IN A 5-GAL BUCKET.  THE CONTAINER WAS BROUGHT BACK TO THE LTC TERMINAL IN CHARLESTON, SC FOR RE-INSPECTION TO ENSURE FITTING WAS PROPERLY REPAIRED.  THE CONTAINER WAS THEN RE-DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE THE NEXT DAY.  THE RELEASED PRODUCT THAT WAS CONTAINED IN THE BUCKET WAS RETAINED BY THE CUSTOMER AND DISPOSED OF ACCORDING TO THEIR PROCEDURES.
NO REMARKS

CSXT'S DISTRICT SUPERINTENDENT NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER'S FACILITY IN INDIANAPOLIS. THE SHIPPER SENT RESCAR, A RAILCAR REPAIR CONTRACTOR, TO MAKE REPAIRS. THIS CAR IS A TWO COMPARTMENT CAR. THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVES ON BOTH COMPARTMENTS WERE DRIPPING. BUCKETS WERE PLACED UNDER THE VALVES TO CONTAIN THE DRIPS. RESCAR FOUND THAT THE OPERATING LEVERS ON THE JAMES BERRY WAFER VALVES WERE NOT "LOCKED" IN THE CLOSED POSITION EVEN THOUGH THE LEVERS WERE PHYSICALLY PENNED IN THE CLOSED POSITION. column168: A CAR INSPECTOR AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN FLINT, MI REPORTED A STRONG LP GAS ODOR ON TRACK C-15 WHICH CONTAINS SEVERAL LPG CARS BUT HE COULD NOT ID WHICH CAR WAS POSSIBLY LEAKING. THE YARD WAS EVACUATED AS A PRECAUTION AND THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT WAS NOTIFIED. AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS DISPATCHED TO CHECK FOR FLAMMABILITY, TO ID THE LEAKING CAR & MAKE REPAIRS. THE RAILROAD'S MECHANICAL FOREMAN WAS INSPECTING THE YARD AND FOUND THE ODOR WAS COMING FROM A CGTX 63639,, RES LP GAS. HE INSPECTED VALVES IN THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING & FOUND VAPORS LEAKING FROM THE PACKING GLAND NUT ON THE GAUGING DEVICE. THE CONTRACTOR TEAM VERIFIED WITH A GAS METER & WITH SNOOP SOLUTION THAT THIS WAS THE ONLY SOURCE OF THE VAPOR RELEASE. THEY TIGHTENED THE PACKAGING GLAND NUT 2 COMPLETE TURNS BY HAND AND THEN TIGHTENED IT 2 MORE TURNS WITH A WRENCH. THEY CHECKED AGAIN WITH THE GAS METER AND WITH THE SNOOP SOLUTION TO CONFIRM THE LEAK HAD BEEN STOPPED. YARD OPERATIONS RECOMMENCED & THE CAR WAS RELEASED.

THE DRIVER WAS IN TRANSIT FROM ONE CUSTOMER SITE TO ANOTHER CUSTOMER.  WHEN HE WAS MOVING DRUMS IN THE BACK OF HIS TRUCK FROM A PREVIOUS PICK-UP, HE DISCOVERED THAT A 55 GALLON STEEL DRUM HAD DEVELOPED A PINHOLE LEAK AND SPILLED 10 GALLON OF PRESS WASH SOLVENT INTO THE BACK OF THE TRUCK.  THE 55 GALLON DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY OVERPACKED INTO A 85 GALLON SALVAGE DRUM AND THE SPILL CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL WHICH WAS PLACED INTO THE SALVAGE DRUM ALSO. NONE OF THE SOLVENT WENT BEYOND THE BACK OF THE TRUCK.  THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 100 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 633 EAST 138TH STREET IN DOLTON, IL FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM INSPECTION TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

SOME DRUMS WERE BEING MOVED IN THE WAREHOUSE AT A TEN DAY STORAGE FACILITY AND A 5 GALLON METAL DRUM WAS SITTING ON TOP OF A 55 GALLON DRUM THAT WAS BEING MOVED.  THE 5 GALLON DRUM FELL OFF AND SPILLED 3 GALLONS OF FLAMMABLE LIQUID INTO A SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AREA.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS WASHED DOWN INTO A SUMP AND THEN PUMPED INTO ANOTHER DRUM.  THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 40 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL MATERIAL, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 3700 LAGRANGE ROAD IN SMITHFIELD, KY FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL.  THE FORKLIFT DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM SECUREMENT AND FORKLIFT HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

THE SAFETY DEPARTMENT NOTIFIED ONYX ENVIRONMENTAL OF THE SITUATION.  ONYX PROCEEDED TO SEND OUT ENVIRONMENTAL PRODUCTS AND SERVICES TO RESPOND TO THE SITE.  UPON ARRIVAL EP&S ASSESSED THE SITUATION. column168: DURING THE UNLOADING PHASE OF TRAILER AT CONSIGNEE FACILITY, CONSIGNEE NOTICE A 1-2 OZ. OF MATERIAL HAD LEAKED FROM THE TOTE-TANK ONTO TRAILER FLOOR. CONSIGNEE ALERTED THEIR IN-HOUSE SPILL RESPONSE TEAM TO FURTHER EXAMINE LEAKAGE. INVESTIGATION FOUND THAT THERE WAS A LOOSE FITTING/VALVE ON TOP SIDE OF TOTE-TANK THAT WAS ALLOWING A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT TO ESCAPE AROUND FITTING DURING MOVEMENT OF TANK. CONSIGNEE SPILL RESPONSE TEAM CORRECTED LOOSE FITTING ON TANK, CONTAINED SPILL IN TRAILER AND REMOVED FOR DISPOSAL. SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CONFINED TO TRAILER FLOOR ONLY.

DRIVER WAS ENROUTE TO CUSTOMER TO DELIVER LOAD. DRIVER STOPPED AT REST AREA AND PARKED UNIT TO ATTEND TO PERSONAL COMFORT. WHEN DRIVER RETURNED TO TRAILER HE OBSERVED WHAT HE THOUGHT WAS A DAMP SPOT ON THE LOWER FRONT END OF TANK. HE OBSERVED IT FOR SEVERAL MINUTES AND SAW WHAT HE BELIEVED TO BE A WIDENING OF THE DAMP SPOT. DRIVER CHECKED TO SEE IF IT WAS CONDENSATION AND WASN'T SURE. AT THIS POINT HE PUT A PAIL UNDER THE FRONT OF UNIT AND THEN OBSERVED A DRIP OF FLUID. THE DRIP WAS APPROXIMATELY ON DROP EVERY MINUTE. HE CALLED THE SAFETY DEPARTMENT. WE HAD HIM SECURE THE AREA AND CONTINUE TO CATCH THE DRIPPING LIQUID IN A PAIL UNTIL WE ARRIVED ON SCENE AND TRANSFERRED THE LOAD INTO ANOTHER TANKER. THE LEAKING UNIT WHEN IT WAS EMPTIED WAS TAKEN TO A TANK WASH FACILITY AND CLEANED AND SENT TO A TANK REPAIR SHOP. NO PRODUCT ESCAPED INTO THE ENVIRONMENT OR WAS LOST ONTO THE GROUND. THE TRANFER WAS DONE BY THE DRIVERS AND A MEMBER OF MANAGEMENT FOR THE COMPANY.

UPON RECEIVING THAT REPORT, THE CARRIER MADE NOTIFICATIONS TO THE TEXAS NATURAL RESOURCE CONSERVATION COMMISSION AND TO THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT.  A  SECOND TRAILER WAS BROUGHT IN TO MOVE THE UNAFFECTED DRUMS TO .  THE CONTRACTOR CONTINUED WORKING AND FOUND ONE DRUM NEARLY EMPTY.  THE ENTIRE TRAILER WAS UNLOADED. IN THE PROCESS, A THIRD LEAKING DRUM WAS DISCOVERED.  THE THREE DAMAGED DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED AND LEFT ON THE ORIGINAL TRAILER.  OIL DRY WAS SPREAD OVER THE ENTIRE TRAILER FLOOR.  IT WAS RETURNED TO THE CARRIER'S FACILITY AND TAKEN OUT OF SERVICE FOR CLEANING AT A WASHOUT FACILITY.  THE BALANCE OF THE SHIPMENT WAS INSPECTED AND ALLOWED TO CONTINUE TO ITS CONSIGNESS.

column168: THE SITE IS LOCATED ALONG INDUSTRIAL PARKWAY AT THE NORTH END OF THE JEFFERSONVILLE RESEARCH AND INDUSTRIAL PARK.  THE GENERAL LOCATION OF THE SITE IS SHOWN IN ATTACHMENT 1. DENNY TRANSPORT, INC. HAS OPERATED A TRUCKING COMPANY AT THE SITE SINCE 1991.  THE SITE SERVES AS THE COMPANY'S OFFICE, MAINTENANCE GARAGE AND STORAGE YARD.  TRACTORS AND TRAILERS ARE PARKED ON THE ASPHALT AND GRAVEL COVERED AREA AROUND THE OFFICE/GARAGE BUILDING.  A CHAIN LINK FENCE SURROUNDS THE SITE. LAND USE IN THE SURROUNDING AREA IS PREDOMINATELY COMMERCIAL AND INDUSTRIAL.  THE AREA TO THE EAST, ACROSS INDUSTRIAL PARKWAY, IS OCCUPIED BY THE INDY CONTAINER GROUP, S & R TIRE SERVICE, AND ANDERSON BROTHERS PAVING.  THE AREA TO THE WEST IS OCCUPIED BY A RAIL YARD, A FORMER BIGFOOT SERVICE STATION, AND A FORMER FERTILIZER PLANT/SALT TERMINAL.  THE AREA TO THE NORTH IS OCCUPIED BY SEVERAL RAILROAD TRACKS.  THE AREA TO THE SOUTH IS OCCUPIED BY THERMOKING OF KENTUCKIANA. THE FOLLOWING SECTIONS OF THIS REPORT DESCRIBE THE RELEASE, THE INITIAL RESPONSE THAT WAS CONDUCTED TO CONTROL THE RELEASE, THE EXCAVATION ACTIVITIES THAT WERE CONDUCTED TO REMEDIATE THE IMPACTED SOIL AND THE INVESTIGATION THAT WAS CONDUCTED TO ASSESS GROUNDWATER IMPACTS. A RELEASE OF PRINTING INK WAS DISCOVERED AT THE DENNY TRANSPORT FACILITY ON SEPTEMBER 4, 2000.  THE RELEASE OCCURRED WHEN VANDALS OPENED THE VALVES ON THE BOTTOM OF THE TANKER TRAILER STORED IN THE PARKING AREA.  IT IS ESTIMATED THAT A TOTAL OF APPROXIMATELY 5,100-GALLONS OF INK WERE LOST AS A RESULT OF THE RELEASE. THE INK IS A SOLVENT BASED MATERIAL MANUFACTURED BY THE FLINT INK COMPANY IN NEW ALBANY, INDIANA.  THE INK CONSISTS OF APPROXIMATELY 54 PERCENT TOLUENE, 1.5 PERCENT XYLENES AND 0.5 PERCENT ETHYL BENZENE.  THE SPECIFIC GRAVITY IS LESS THAN ONE AND THE SOLUBILITY IS LESS THAN ONE PERCENT.  A MATERIALS SAFETY DATA SHEET DESCRIBING THE INK IS PROVIDED IN ATTACHMENT 2. FOLLOWING THE RELEASE, THE INK FLOWED ACROSS THE GRAVEL SURFACE AND ASPHALT DRIVEWAY TO A LOW LYING GRASS AREA AND DRAINAGE DITCH LOCATED ALONG INDUSTRIAL PARKWAY.  THE MAJORITY OF THE INK POOLED IN A LOW LYING AREA AT THE NORTH END OF THE SITE.  PORTIONS OF THE INK ALSO MIGRATED TO THE GRAVEL FILL MATERIAL UNDERLYING THE ASPHALT DRIVEWAY AND TO THE BACKFILL SURROUNDING A WATER MAIN RUNNING PARALLEL TO INDUSTRIAL PARKWAY.  THE APPROXIMATE LOCATION OF THE RELEASE AND THE DIRECTION OF SURFACE MIGRATION ARE SHOWN IN ATTACHMENT 3. UPON DISCOVERING THE RELEASE, DENNY TRANSPORT, INC. CONTACTED MIDWEST ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. TO INITIATE THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE.  DENNY TRANSPORT ALSO CONTACTED THE JEFFERSONVILLE POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENTS. column168: ON SEPTEMBER 9, 2000, AT 10:30 A.M., AN ENVIRONMENTAL INCIDENT OCCURRED WHICH INVOLVED ONE HYDROCHEM CHEMICAL TRANSPORT WHICH WAS IN THE PROCESS OF TRANSPORTING HYDROCHLORIC ACID. THE INCIDENT OCCURRED WHILE TRAVELING EAST ON HIGHWAY 24 AT THE TELEGRAPH EXIT. DOT FORM F 5800.1 HAS ALSO BEEN INCLUDED TO SATISFY WRITTEN REPORTING REQUIREMENTS. APPROXIMATELY 12 GALLONS (120 LBS.) OF 36% HYDROCHLORIC ACID SPILLED TO THE ROADWAY WHEN A VALVE ON THE TANK BEGAN TO LEAK WHILE IN TRANSIT. THE SPILLED ACID WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH AND ALL WASTE MATERIALS WERE COLLECTED FOR DISPOSAL.  ONLY ONE LANE OF THE HIGHWAY WAS CLOSED, FOR A PERIOD OF 30 MINUTES, WHILE THE CLEAN-UP OPERATIONS WERE COMPLETED. THE INCIDENT AND CLEAN-UP WERE MONITORED BY THE CALIFORNIA HIGHWAY PATROL AND LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL WHO WERE ON THE SCENE. WE ARE UNAWARE OF ANY DAMAGE TO PROPERTY OR TO INDIVIDUALS. THIS AMOUNT DOES NOT CONSTITUTE A REPORTABLE QUANTITY FOR HYDROCHLORIC ACID AND THERE IS NO PRESENT OR FUTURE DANGER TO THE PUBLIC AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT.  AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT, ADDITIONAL HAZMAT TRANSPORTATION TRAINING IS BEING GIVEN TO ALL BRANCH EMPLOYEES. ADDITIONALLY, EFFORTS HAVE BEEN MADE TO ENSURE THAT ALL VALVES HAVE A CAP ON THEM WITH A SUFFICIENT SEAL TO RETAIN LIQUIDS DURING TRANSPORT.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER AT THE ICTF. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE ICTF, LOCATED THE ABOVE CONTAINER IN YELLOW #509, WHERE A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT (LESS THAN 1 PINT) WAS NOTED ON THE PAVEMENT AT THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER.  THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK WHERE IT COULD BE SECURED AND ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  UPON OPENING THE REAR DOORS, NOTED FOUR EACH 2X6 PIECES OF LUMBER IN A HORIZONTAL POSITION, SET TO THE REAR BULL SLOTS.  TOW LARGE DID BAGS HAD BEEN PLACED DIRECTLY BETWEEN THE BULL BOARDS AND THE DOUBLE STACKED DRUMS.  THIS IS NOT A RECOMMENDED PROTOCOL, NOR IS IT AN APPROVED METHOD PER THE BOE 6C FOR THE PROPER SECUREMENT OF HAZARDOUS COMMODITIES TRANSPORTED BY RAIL.  AFTER IDENTIFYING MOL AS THE SHIPPER OF RECORD ON THE RAIL BILLING, IT WAS DECIDED TO HAVE THE UNIT SIT TILL MORNING WHEN THE MOL CHICAGO OFFICE WOULD BE OPEN FOR BUSINESS.  CONTACT WAS MADE WITH MOL, WHO REQUESTED THE CONTAINER BE INSPECTED.  DEVELOPED THROUGH THE MARINE SURVEYOR THAT THE LOAD BELONGED TO GOLDSCHMIDT CHEMICAL, POINT OF ORIGIN HAD NOT BEEN IDENTIFIED AT THIS STAGE.  LATER IN THE AFTERNOON, TEC ADVISED MOL HAD GIVEN THEM A VERBAL AUTHORIZATION TO REWORK THE CONTAINER.  THE FOLLOWING MORNING, THURSDAY, 9-14-00, THE LADING WAS REMOVED AND INSPECTED FOR LEAKS.  WHILE IN THE PROCESS OF WORKING THE LADING, MOL'S SURVEYOR PRODUCED AN E-MAIL DOCUMENT FROM GOLDSCHMIDT CHEMICAL IDENTIFYING THE REPRESENTATIVE THAT AUTHORIZED THE REWORK.  AFTER DISCUSSING THE CONDITION OF THE LADING AND THE METHOD OF SECUREMENT, TEC WAS PUT IN DIRECT CONTACT WITH GOLDSCHMIDT.  AS THE DRUMS WERE BEING OFF LOADED, LOCATED ONE DRUM IN THE TOP TIER, FIVE ROWS FROM THE NOSE, SECOND OUT FROM THE LEFT SIDE WALL, TO BE THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  THE BOTTOM ROLLING HOOP HAD BEEN IMPACTED, CAUSING A SMALL 'V' INDENTATION AND CRACK IN THE ROLLING HOOP.    PRODUCT WAS ACTIVELY LEAKING FROM THE DRUM AS IT WAS MOVED.  THE DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO AN OVER PACK FOR SECUREMENT.  IT APPEARS THIS DRUM SUSTAINED THE DAMAGE PRIOR TO OR DURING THE LOADING PROCESS, AS THIS TYPE OF IMPACT TO THE DRUM IS NOT NORMALLY FOUND IF ABRADING AGAINST AN ADJACENT DRUM DURING TRANSIT.  FOUR ADDITIONAL DRUMS WERE LOCATED WITH SUFFICIENT DAMAGE TO WARRANT THEM UNFIT FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT.  THE FLOORING WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE, AND THE REMAINING DRUMS WERE RELOADED INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER.  THE LADING WAS PROPERLY BLOCKED AND BRACED, THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

RESCAR WAS ALSO CALLED BY THE SHIPPER.  THE NEXT DAY THE CAR WAS REPAIRED BY RESCAR.  NO WATERWAYS, DRAINS OR ENVIRONMENTAL ISSUES.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1615 HOURS, SEPTEMBER 12, 2000, STEPHEN MEARNS, AN APRIA EMPLOYEE, WAS TRAVELING NORTH BOUND ON I-25 AT APPROXIMATELY MILE MARKER #154, IN AN APRIA VEHICLE, 1996 ISUZU FRR, VIN # JALF5A12XT3700482 WHEN HE NOTICED WHAT HE THOUGHT WAS SMOKE COMING FROM THE RIGHT REAR OF HIS VEHICLE. HE IMMEDIATELY PULLED OFF ONTO THE DIRT SHOULDER OF THE ROADWAY. HE ENGAGED HIS EMERGENCY FLASHERS, SET THE PARKING BRAKE, SHUT OFF THE MOTOR AND EXITED THE VEHICLE. UPON EXITING THE VEHICLE HE FOUND THAT THE FILL HOSE FOR THE HL190 CARGO TANK MOUNTED IN THE VEHICLE HAD FALLEN OUT OF THE SIDE DOOR AND HAD EITHER BEEN DRIVEN OVER OR CAUGHT ON AN UNKNOWN OBJECT. THIS HAD RESULTED IN A FITTING AT THE VALVE RUPTURING ON THE CARGO TANK. THIS HAD ALLOWED THE RELEASE OF OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID ONTO THE DIRT SHOULDER. A VOLUNTEER FIRE FIGHTER HAD BEEN BEHIND HIM ON THE HIGHWAY AND SAW THE SMOKE (ACTUALLY VAPOR) ALSO PULLED OFF AND OFFERED ASSISTANCE.UPON FINDING OUT WHAT HAD HAPPENED THEY BOTH MOVED BACK FROM THE VEHICLE. THE FIRE FIGHTER USED HIS CELL PHONE TO CONTACT THE DEPARTMENT AND THE COLORADO HIGHWAY PATROL. MEARNS CALLED HIS SUPERVISOR TO MAKE HIS EMERGENCY NOTIFICATION. UPON ARRIVAL OF THE FIRE DEPARTMENT THEY FOUND THAT THE CARGO TANK HAD FINISHED DRAINING ONTO THE DIRT SHOULDER. THE FIRE PERSONNEL PROCEEDED TO HOSE THE AREA DOWN WITH WATER. THIS WARMED THE OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID TO ACCELERATE ITS CONVERSION TO A GASEOUS STATE AND SUBSEQUENT EVAPORATION. ONCE THE VAPOR CLOUD CLEARED THEY DEEMED THE SITE SAFE AND LEFT. THE COLORADO HIGHWAY ISSUED MEARNS A CITATION FOR INCIDENTAL RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. THERE WAS NO INJURIES OR COLLATERAL DAMAGE.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY ICTF SECURITY REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE ICTF, LOCATED THE ABOVE CONTAINER IN ROW E-5, SPACE 199, AND OBSERVED A SMALL AMOUNT OF DRIED PRODUCT AT THE RIGHT REAR CORNER OF THE CONTAINER. LESS THAN 1 PINT OF PRODUCT HAD WEPT THROUGH THE REAR DOOR GASKET AND POOLED ONTO THE REAR PLATFORM OF THE CHASSIS. THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK WHERE IT COULD CONTAINED AND ISOLATED. UPON OPENING THE REAR DOORS OF THE CONTAINER, NOTED THE LADING TO BE 55 GALLON DRUMS, DOUBLE STACKED, AND SECURED WITH TY-PATCH. THE 4 STRIPS OF TY-PATCH WERE LOOSE AND THE FABRIC HAD SHIFTED DOWN. IT WAS ALSO NOTED THAT THE DRUMS WERE THE NEWER TYPE WITH THE INVERTED SIDE WALL ROLLING HOOPS. PLYWOOD HAD BEEN USED FOR THE BI LEVEL SEPARATION, AND IT WAS NOTED THAT ALL THE SHEETS HAD BEEN CUT SHORT. INSTEAD OF REACHING FROM SIDE WALL TO WALL, THE PLYWOOD HAD BEEN SHORT CUT ON THE AVERAGE 6-8 INCHES. WITH THE GAP BETWEEN THE END OF THE PLYWOOD AND THE CONTAINER SIDE WALL, THERE WAS NO CONTINUOUS FLAT SURFACE FOR THE TOP TIER DRUMS TO REST ON, WHICH WOULD ALLOW THE DRUMS TO ROCK AND MOVE WHILE IN TRANSIT. THIS COULD ACCOUNT FOR THE LOOSE TY-PATCH CONDITION AT THE REAR OF THE LOAD. IN ORDER TO LOCATE THE LEAKING DRUM, THE LADING WOULD HAVE TO BE REMOVED. UPON CONTACTING THE SHIPPER, DEGUSSA-HULS, ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO REMOVE AND INSPECT THE LADING. DEGUSSA HAD THEIR LOCAL CONTRACTOR, ECOLOGY CONTROL,  RESPOND AND PROVIDE THE PERSONNEL TO COMPLETE THE WORK. ONE DRUM WAS LOCATED ON THE TOP STACK, MID SHIP THAT APPEARED TO BE THE LEAKER. CLOSER INSPECTION DEVELOPED THE DRUM HAD A SMALL ONE INCH GROOVE, SIMILAR TO A KNIFE CUT, IN THE SIDE WALL, LOCATED JUST ABOVE THE BOTTOM CHIME. THE GROOVE APPEARED TO BE A PAINT SCRAPE AND WAS NOT LEAKING AT THE TIME IT WAS REMOVED. IT APPEARS THIS DAMAGE WAS DONE PRIOR TO, OR DURING THE LOADING PROCESS. IT IS SUSPECTED THE DRUM WAS 'NICKED' WITH THE CORNER OF A DRUM GRAPPLER ATTACHED TO A FORK LIFT. WHEN THE PRODUCT WEPT FROM THE SIDE WALL GROOVE,  IT CREATED A VACUUM IN THE DRUM THAT HELD THE PRODUCT UNTIL THE LIQUID WAS DISTURBED BY MOTION. UPON FLIPPING THE DRUM OVER AIR WA SUCKED BACK INTO THE DRUM. THE DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACE INTO AN OVERPACK FOR SECUREMENT. THE CONTAINER SURFACE AREAS AND REMAINING DRUMS WERE CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE, AND THE LADING PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER. THE CONTAINER WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

ON 9-28-00, AN EDWARDS OIL CO TANK WAGON DRIVER DELIVERED FUEL OIL FOR HOME HEATING TO A RESIDENTIAL CUSTOMER.  WHEN HE MADE HIS DELIVERY, HE WAS UNAWARE THAT THE HOMEOWNER HAD REMOVED THE FUEL OIL STORAGE TANK FROM THE BASEMENT WITHOUT PLACING CAPS ON THE FILL PIPES STILL PROTRUDING INTO THE BASEMENT.  AS A RESULT, THE PRODUCT WAS SPILLED ONTO THE CONCRETE OF THE BASEMENT FLOOR, AN UNKNOWN QUANTITY OF PRODUCT FLOWED THROUGH THE BASEMENT FLOOR DRAIN INTO THE CITY SANITARY SEWER SYSTEM.  THE HOMEOWNER WAS NOT HOME AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT, SO DID NOT INFORM EDWARDS OIL COMPANY OF THE SPILL UNTIL SATURDAY, 9-30-00.  ALL CONTAMINATED ITEMS FROM THE BASEMENT WERE REMOVED FOR DISPOSAL AND.  THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS CLEANED FROM THE BASEMENT FLOOR.

column168: FRIDAY, SEPTEMBER 8, 2000 APPROXIMATELY 1:30 WHILE ON THE NW SIDE OF FORT WORTH, I RECEIVED A CALL FROM KEITH.  HE INFORMED ME THAT HE HAD JUST SPILLED BLEACH ONTO THE PARKING LOT AT SOUTHEAST YMCA.  THE HOSE HAD COME LOOSE FROM THE REEL AND BLEACH HAD PUMPED DIRECTLY ONTO THE TRUCK AND THE PARKING LOT.  HE ALREADY HAD IT STOPPED WHEN HE CONTACTED ME, BUT HE DID NOT HAVE A SPILL KIT ON THE TRUCK.  MOST OF THE BLEACH PUDDLED IN THE PARKING LOT, BUT SOME WAS RUNNING SLOWLY ALONG A CURB DOWN THE STREET.  I SUGGESTED HE GET SOME DIRT IN FRONT OF THE STREAM TO CONTAIN IT.  HE DID. MEANWHILE, I LOCATED WAYNE ON I20 EASTBOUND FROM GRAND PRAIRIE.  I SENT HIM BY THE OFFICE TO PICK UP CLEANUP SUPPLIES THAT I HAD JAVIER GATHER AND HAVE READY TO LOAD.  JAVIER WENT WITH WAYNE AND HIS HELPER, MIGUEL.  THE 16 GALLONS OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE WAS CONTAINED, NEUTRALIZED AND PUMPED INTO A CONTAINER.  THE REMAINDER WAS ABSORBED WITH SAND THEN SHOVELED AND SWEPT UP.  WAYNE BROUGHT THE RECOVERED AMOUNT AND THE SAND TO DCC.  I CONTACTED DPC FOR ADVICE WHEN I ARRIVED AT THE OFFICE LATER.  AT 5:05PM I CALLED THE AFTER-HOURS AUSTIN NUMBER THAT GREG HARTHCOCK GAVE ME FOR TNRCC.  I GOT A RECORDING SO I CALLED THE 817 NUMBER AND THAT WAS ALSO A RECORDING.  I WENT ABOUT THE OFFICE CHECKING PAPERWORK, DELIVERIES, MESSAGES, ETC.  I TRIED AGAIN AFTER 6PM AND GOT THROUGH TO THE AUSTIN NUMBER.  RYAN TOOK THE BASIC INFORMATION AND HE SAID THAT SOMEONE WOULD CALL ME.  JUST AFTER I LOCKED UP THE OFFICE ABOUT 7PM, THE PAGER WENT OFF SO I WENT BACK INTO THE OFFICE TO RETURN PHONE CALLS.  THE SERVICE GAVE ME A NUMBER TO CONTACT JAN MALONE, TNRCC.  THE NUMBER DIDN'T WORK SO I VERIFIED IT WITH THE ANSWERING SERVICE. THEY HAD THE SAME NUMBER SO I LEFT A MESSAGE WITH THEM THAT IF SHE CALLED BACK AGAIN TO GET A DIFFERENT NUMBER.  I CALLED THE AUSTIN NUMBER AGAIN AND LEFT A MESSAGE.  I DIDN'T HEAR ANY MORE FROM HER UNTIL MONDAY WHEN I CALLED HER AT HER OFFICE.

column168: ON 14 SEPTEMBER 2000, DRIVER ROBERT ROSE WAS DISPATCHED IN TRACTOR 354 AND PULLING TRAILER 2153 WITH A LOAD OF 93% SULFURIC ACID FROM PVS IN COPLEY, OH TO BE DELIVERED TO AK STEEL IN MANSFIELD, OH. DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS AT ABOUT 1705 HOURS, THE PRODUCT HOSE FAILED AND THERE WAS AN ESTIMATED 200 GALLONS OF PRODUCT SPILLED. THE RQ FOR THIS PRODUCT IS 1,000 POUNDS WHICH EQUALS APPROXIMATELY 64.5 GALLONS. FORTUNATELY, THE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED INTO A CONTAINMENT SYSTEM SO IT IS CONSIDERED A CONTROLLED SPILL AND NO DOT 5800.1 MUST BE GENERATED. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR DAMAGE TO EQUIPMENT REPORTED AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT. THE HOSE WAS REPLACED AND THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS UNLOADED WITHOUT INCIDENT. AS A MATTER OF POLICY AT THE AK STEEL PLANT THE DRIVER WAS REQUIRED TO PROVIDE A URINALYSIS SPECIMEN AS WELL AS A BAC. BOTH TESTS WERE NEGATIVE. ACCORDING TO THE DRIVER, HE WAS NEAR THE CAB OF THE TRACTOR WHEN HE HEARD WHAT HE DESCRIBED AS A LOUD POP. WHEN HE GOT TO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER HE OBSERVED THE SPRAYING ACID FROM OUR PRODUCT HOSE. HE THEN CLOSED THE INTERNAL VALVE USING THE PUMP LEAVER AND THEN THE EXTERNAL VALVE. HE STATED THAT HE IMMEDIATELY REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO AK STEEL PERSONNEL WHO IMMEDIATELY BEGAN SPREADING SODA ASH ON THE PRODUCT TO NEUTRALIZE IT. HE STATED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS BEING SWEPT TO THE PLANTS ACID RECOVERY SYSTEM. HOWEVER, HE WAS NOT CERTAIN IF PRODUCT LANDED OUTSIDE OF THE CONTAINMENT AREA. GREAT WEST CASUALTY COMPANY WAS CONTACTED TO PROTECT OUR INTEREST. THEY ARE ASSIGNING CUSTARD INSURANCE TO THE CLAIM. HELEN JETT (PVS) WAS ADVISED OF THE INCIDENT AT ABOUT 1800 HOURS. ANTICIPATING THAT THE PRODUCT WAS NOT PROPERLY CONTAINED, I CONTACTED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO PO3 ARSENAULT. I EXPLAINED THAT THE PRODUCT MAY HAVE BEEN CONTAINED BY THE CONSIGNEE'S SYSTEM AND THAT THIS REPORT MAY BE DELETED IF IT WAS DECLARED A "CONTROLLED SPILL." INCIDENT NUMBER 542164 WAS ASSIGNED TO THIS CASE. AT ABOUT 1900 HOURS, I SPOKE WITH JAMES HOWARD (AK STEEL SAFETY DIRECTOR) WHO CONFIRMED THAT THE INCIDENT HAD OCCURRED AS DESCRIBED BY THE DRIVER. HE ESTIMATED THAT THE QUANTITY OF PRODUCT WAS LESS THAN 200 GALLONS AND THAT THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN THE SYSTEM. HE ALSO STATED THAT GRADY MEDEWIG (AK STEEL ENVIRONMENTAL OFFICER) DETERMINED THAT THE SPILL WAS ENTIRELY CONTAINED AND THAT THE INCIDENT WAS NON-REPORTABLE. THE INITIAL INVESTIGATION OF THE INCIDENT REVEALED THAT THE PRODUCT HOSE HAD NOT BEEN RECERTIFIED SINCE 9/5/97. THE COMPANY POLICY REQUIRES HOSES TO BE TESTED ANNUALLY. HOW THE HOSE SLIPPED THROUGH THE CERTIFICATION PROCESS IS UNCLEAR. AT 1905 HOURS I CONTACTED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND ADVISED THEM THAT THE INCIDENT WAS A CONTROLLED SPILL. PO3 ARSENAULT STATED THAT THE EPA HAD BEEN ADVISED AND THAT I WOULD HAVE TO REPORT THE INFORMATION TO THEM THE FOLLOWING DAY.
